WEBVTT

00:31.699 --> 00:32.950
(METAL CLANKS)

00:33.784 --> 00:35.120
(SIGHING)

01:25.002 --> 01:26.086
Hello, Patty.

01:34.595 --> 01:35.679
(SCREAMING)

01:37.097 --> 01:38.474
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

01:47.733 --> 01:52.863
♪ I heard you threw
your man around

01:54.782 --> 02:00.204
♪ Pick him up
just to let him down

02:00.204 --> 02:05.335
♪ It's a shame, baby,
but I always knew

02:06.669 --> 02:10.756
♪ Just the way
you're gonna do

02:10.756 --> 02:12.132
Incredible words
today, Reverend.

02:12.132 --> 02:13.551
Thank you
very much.

02:17.012 --> 02:22.226
♪ Just a psychotic girl
and I won't get lost... ♪

02:22.226 --> 02:23.644
It's a beautiful day.

02:23.644 --> 02:24.687
Oh, it's hot.

02:28.316 --> 02:30.776
Did you see the new carriage
the Andersons have?

02:30.776 --> 02:33.112
EMMA: Father prefers
we walk.

02:34.071 --> 02:35.155
Mr. Borden,
how is everything?

02:35.155 --> 02:37.408
Fine, fine, fine.

02:37.408 --> 02:39.244
Your daughters
are looking lovely.

02:39.244 --> 02:41.371
Lovely?

02:41.371 --> 02:45.040
If they're so lovely,
why don't I have
many grandchildren by now?

02:58.846 --> 03:02.600
Are we having
the mutton again
for lunch today?

03:02.600 --> 03:04.602
You don't have to
eat it.

03:04.602 --> 03:08.272
I do worry it's making us
all sick.

03:08.272 --> 03:12.276
You will eat what's put
in front of you,
or you won't eat at all.

03:35.716 --> 03:37.343
May I please be excused?

03:39.470 --> 03:40.721
No, Lizzie, you may not.

03:45.934 --> 03:47.019
Excuse me, Father.

03:54.276 --> 03:56.028
(LIZZIE HUMMING)

04:17.716 --> 04:20.636
I've asked you
not to make noise
while I'm in this room.

04:26.475 --> 04:27.893
Pardon me.

05:00.134 --> 05:02.094
MR. BORDEN: What are you
doing here, Sousa?

05:02.094 --> 05:04.471
Don't you ever
come to my house.

05:04.471 --> 05:06.515
SOUSA: I need to
pay my men.

05:06.515 --> 05:09.518
You can't cheat us,
Mr. Borden.
We've had enough.

05:09.518 --> 05:13.272
You get paid for
the work that you do,
not a penny more.

05:13.272 --> 05:15.441
SOUSA: You're not gonna
get away with this.

05:23.574 --> 05:25.325
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

05:25.325 --> 05:28.328
Mrs. Borden,
the church is
always short of funds.

05:28.328 --> 05:31.957
♪ Fight the horde,
scratch the nails

05:34.126 --> 05:39.006
♪ 'Ware the charging
lion's tails

05:40.383 --> 05:44.052
♪ In all the blackest
of the blues

05:44.052 --> 05:48.724
♪ I need a longer fuse
Whenever I... ♪

05:48.724 --> 05:51.769
My father thinks
he can forbid me
from going.

05:51.769 --> 05:53.771
What will he do?
Lock you in your room?

05:53.771 --> 05:55.856
(SCOFFS) Believe me,
he would if he could.

05:56.482 --> 05:57.566
How is Emma doing?

05:59.527 --> 06:04.449
I love my sister,
but she likes to
hide her head in the sand.

06:05.491 --> 06:07.326
I've always wanted more,

06:07.326 --> 06:10.204
more than she's wanted.

06:10.204 --> 06:11.538
I just wish
I had the freedom

06:11.538 --> 06:13.791
to live the life
I've always imagined.

06:13.791 --> 06:16.543
Nothing wrong
with dreaming, Lizzie.
Hmm.

06:18.670 --> 06:20.547
It's difficult to
dream in that place.

06:23.050 --> 06:25.385
Sometimes, Alice,

06:25.385 --> 06:28.472
I have a feeling that
something terrible
is going to happen there.

06:29.431 --> 06:31.600
What do you mean?

06:31.600 --> 06:35.521
Well, my father
has so many enemies.

06:35.521 --> 06:40.150
There have been
so many arguments
and disputes.

06:40.150 --> 06:42.653
I fear someone
might try to hurt him.

06:46.449 --> 06:47.991
Miss Borden,
your mother said that

06:47.991 --> 06:51.454
we aren't to extend
any more credit to you
without her permission.

06:51.454 --> 06:52.663
Oh. (CHUCKLES)

06:52.663 --> 06:54.998
Well, how embarrassing.

06:55.916 --> 06:57.209
(SIGHS)

06:57.209 --> 06:59.378
I suppose I'll have to pay
the old-fashioned way.

06:59.378 --> 07:00.754
That would be fine.

07:03.508 --> 07:04.716
Thank you.

07:16.521 --> 07:18.021
All ready, Miss Borden.

07:18.021 --> 07:19.649
Wonderful.

07:19.649 --> 07:20.983
I'll have Bridget
come by and pick it up.

07:20.983 --> 07:22.568
Of course.

07:22.568 --> 07:23.986
I hope you enjoy your party.

07:23.986 --> 07:25.529
Thank you.

07:57.686 --> 07:59.479
(CREAKING)

08:01.273 --> 08:02.482
Father?

08:05.528 --> 08:07.029
What are you doing?

08:09.448 --> 08:11.617
Father's upset.

08:11.617 --> 08:14.620
Did you steal a mirror
from the dress shop?

08:14.620 --> 08:16.830
The owner said
you took a mirror
from her store.

08:16.830 --> 08:18.540
That's ridiculous.

08:18.540 --> 08:20.167
Why do you lie to me, Lizzie?

08:20.167 --> 08:21.293
I don't lie to you.

08:21.293 --> 08:23.086
You lie to everyone.

08:24.421 --> 08:25.923
So what did father do?

08:25.923 --> 08:28.133
He paid, of course.

08:31.637 --> 08:33.263
Could we have a moment,
please?

08:37.851 --> 08:39.394
It was an accident.

08:39.394 --> 08:42.607
The mirror must have fallen
into the dress box.

08:42.607 --> 08:44.609
Don't think you're going to
that party tonight.

08:44.609 --> 08:45.734
Of course, I'm going.

08:45.734 --> 08:47.235
Who will be your escort?

08:47.235 --> 08:49.529
I am perfectly capable
of walking there on my own.

08:49.529 --> 08:51.406
I don't need an escort.

08:51.406 --> 08:55.410
I will not have you
traipsing about Fall River
all alone at night.

08:56.787 --> 08:59.582
You will not
go unaccompanied.

09:00.457 --> 09:01.708
Oh, Father.

09:02.752 --> 09:05.671
I do love you so.

09:05.671 --> 09:07.297
But I'm not that
little girl anymore.

09:08.799 --> 09:11.760
No, no, no.
The answer is no.

09:13.220 --> 09:14.888
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

09:21.561 --> 09:23.355
♪ Whoo, boy

09:30.362 --> 09:32.406
♪ Whoo, boy

09:34.700 --> 09:36.661
♪ Give me a shout,
so I'll be hypnotized

09:36.661 --> 09:39.162
♪ With them swinging hips
and them workout thighs

09:39.162 --> 09:41.623
♪ Oh, Lord,
what's a man to do?

09:43.500 --> 09:45.628
♪ Spent all my time at bars

09:45.628 --> 09:47.421
♪ Trying to find
what I'm looking for

09:47.421 --> 09:50.590
♪ But, baby, baby,
I still ain't found you

09:52.009 --> 09:54.344
♪ Whoo, boy!

09:54.344 --> 09:55.762
(LIZZIE LAUGHING)

09:57.640 --> 09:59.307
ALICE: Lizzie!
Alice.

09:59.307 --> 10:00.684
Took you long enough.

10:04.438 --> 10:05.773
Stanley Jefferies.

10:05.773 --> 10:08.984
Lizzie Borden.
Are you actually here?

10:08.984 --> 10:11.570
Think of me
as a figment
of your imagination.

10:11.570 --> 10:13.655
Lizzie, I don't know
much about you.

10:13.655 --> 10:16.783
I've seen you at church,
but never had
the chance to speak.

10:18.243 --> 10:20.037
Aren't you
a Sunday school teacher?

10:20.037 --> 10:21.789
Only on Sundays.

10:23.081 --> 10:24.332
Lizzie.
LIZZIE: Nance.

10:24.332 --> 10:25.793
Lizzie Borden.

10:28.462 --> 10:30.338
Come on, I have some people
I want you to meet.

10:30.338 --> 10:31.674
(BOTH LAUGHING)

10:33.508 --> 10:35.218
♪ Whoo boy! ♪

10:45.187 --> 10:46.646
(DISTANT SCREAMING)

10:59.451 --> 11:00.952
(PIGEONS SCREECHING)

11:00.952 --> 11:02.705
(SCREAMING CONTINUES)

11:12.547 --> 11:13.716
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

11:15.592 --> 11:18.678
Lizzie? Wake up.
You're wanted downstairs.

11:28.856 --> 11:30.941
Lizzie,

11:30.941 --> 11:32.777
there has, uh...

11:32.777 --> 11:33.944
There's been a robbery.

11:35.695 --> 11:37.864
Mrs. Borden's gold watch
and chain were taken

11:37.864 --> 11:41.159
and, uh, $20 in cash.

11:41.159 --> 11:43.746
The watch that
my mother gave me
before she died.

11:43.746 --> 11:45.997
(SIGHS) That's terrible.

11:45.997 --> 11:48.708
Do you have any idea
what might have happened?

11:48.708 --> 11:50.377
Of course not.

11:52.295 --> 11:54.005
Marshall.

11:54.005 --> 11:55.715
Um...

11:55.715 --> 11:59.594
As I was saying, Mr. Borden,
there seems to be no sign
of forced entry.

11:59.594 --> 12:02.097
And since your maid saw
or heard no one enter,

12:02.097 --> 12:03.808
well, I'm inclined
to think that...

12:03.808 --> 12:05.809
Yes?

12:05.809 --> 12:09.897
Perhaps there's
another possible explanation.

12:09.897 --> 12:12.065
Well, Marshall Fleet,
I want to thank you
for your help,

12:12.065 --> 12:13.900
and if we hear
anything more
about the situation,

12:13.900 --> 12:15.735
you'll be the first to know.

12:30.960 --> 12:33.753
What do you have to say
for yourself, Lizzie?

12:33.753 --> 12:36.966
Honestly, Father,
what are you thinking?

12:36.966 --> 12:38.842
We don't see
how anybody else
could have gotten in.

12:38.842 --> 12:40.552
Oh, is that so?

12:40.552 --> 12:41.971
How can she steal
from her own family?

12:41.971 --> 12:44.974
I did not steal those items
from the house, Father.

12:44.974 --> 12:47.267
Nor would I ever
think to do so.

12:47.267 --> 12:48.768
Don't walk away
from me, Lizzie.

12:48.768 --> 12:52.355
Let her go.
Why bother with her anymore?

12:52.355 --> 12:55.901
You let me deal
with my daughter
in my own way, please.

12:57.987 --> 13:00.280
You let her accuse me
of stealing?

13:01.323 --> 13:02.866
In our house?

13:02.866 --> 13:04.869
She's the thief.

13:04.869 --> 13:08.455
The one stealing from you
and me and Emma.

13:08.455 --> 13:10.040
(CHUCKLES)

13:10.040 --> 13:12.250
She's bleeding you dry.

13:12.250 --> 13:16.671
It's her family coming to you
for loans and handouts.

13:16.671 --> 13:19.341
You bought them
that beautiful house
on the hill,

13:19.341 --> 13:24.054
while Emma and I
are prisoners
in this horrible place.

13:24.054 --> 13:28.308
You are blessed to have
a roof over your head.

13:29.976 --> 13:34.899
I have prayed for you.
I protected you.
I have paid for your fines.

13:34.899 --> 13:39.778
And you have
tested and shamed me
as a parent and a Christian.

13:39.778 --> 13:41.989
Have you never felt
grateful in your life?

13:44.909 --> 13:47.912
You don't want me to
become anything, do you?

13:49.120 --> 13:52.207
You just want me
to stay here forever

13:52.207 --> 13:54.042
with you.

13:54.042 --> 13:57.880
No, that's... That's...

13:57.880 --> 14:00.966
Preposterous.
That's preposterous.
That's...

14:00.966 --> 14:02.550
(SIGHS)

14:08.265 --> 14:09.891
It looks handsome on you.

14:11.518 --> 14:14.813
I remember the day
you gave it to me.

14:17.732 --> 14:19.818
You'll find someone.

14:19.818 --> 14:23.446
Someone smart enough to
see you for who you are.

14:23.446 --> 14:25.907
To marry?

14:25.907 --> 14:28.451
What if I don't
want to get married?

14:28.451 --> 14:30.537
You want to grow old alone?

14:31.746 --> 14:32.956
A spinster?

14:35.084 --> 14:37.086
That's not what I meant.

14:37.836 --> 14:39.504
Never mind.

14:45.302 --> 14:47.262
(MUFFLED VOICES)

14:52.142 --> 14:53.184
Lizzie?

14:59.941 --> 15:01.234
I'm leaving for Fairhaven.

15:04.988 --> 15:08.992
My friend Greta had a baby,
so I'm going to
make myself useful.

15:08.992 --> 15:11.161
I shouldn't be
more than a day or two.

15:11.161 --> 15:13.580
Yes, you should
stay a few days.

15:15.874 --> 15:17.084
Lizzie, are you all right?

15:19.836 --> 15:21.005
Perfectly.

15:29.013 --> 15:30.638
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

15:55.413 --> 15:58.541
Bridget, you've got to get
these windows clean
before it gets too hot.

15:58.541 --> 16:00.002
Yes, ma'am.

17:01.020 --> 17:02.647
(CREAKING)

17:04.773 --> 17:06.108
Hello?

17:27.255 --> 17:28.631
(THUDDING)

17:40.727 --> 17:42.187
Morning.
Morning.

17:55.783 --> 17:56.993
MR. BORDEN: Bridget?

17:58.077 --> 18:00.455
Since when do we
lock the dead bolt?

18:00.455 --> 18:02.249
Was the door locked?

18:03.208 --> 18:05.001
No, no, Bridget,

18:05.001 --> 18:07.670
I just like to
knock on my own
front door for a bit.

18:07.670 --> 18:09.380
Beg your pardon,
Mr. Borden.

18:10.673 --> 18:12.217
Where is Mrs. Borden?

18:12.217 --> 18:14.052
I'm not sure. Perhaps...

18:14.052 --> 18:15.345
Mother went out.

18:15.345 --> 18:16.638
She did?

18:16.638 --> 18:18.723
She received a note
from a sick friend.

18:18.723 --> 18:20.058
She must have
gone out to see her.

18:20.642 --> 18:21.768
Oh.

18:24.271 --> 18:25.314
Father?

18:28.274 --> 18:29.651
(SIGHS)

18:31.278 --> 18:32.487
Lizzie?

18:33.947 --> 18:36.157
Lizzie, that's enough.

18:41.496 --> 18:42.580
Are you all right?

18:44.249 --> 18:45.458
Yes.

18:45.458 --> 18:47.085
Why are you sweating so?

18:48.836 --> 18:50.255
It's hot.

18:52.131 --> 18:53.132
I'm glad you're home.

18:55.885 --> 18:56.928
Father?

18:57.303 --> 18:59.222
What?

18:59.222 --> 19:01.641
Are you going
to take a nap?

19:01.641 --> 19:03.185
Yes.

19:07.356 --> 19:08.481
(SIGHS)

19:29.294 --> 19:30.920
(THUD ECHOING)

19:47.186 --> 19:48.272
(SIGHS)

20:21.596 --> 20:22.597
(MR. BORDEN YELLS)

20:25.350 --> 20:26.893
Hello, Patty.
Hello.

20:26.893 --> 20:28.144
How are you?
Fine, thank you.

20:43.576 --> 20:45.203
(SCREAMING)

20:49.458 --> 20:51.167
Miss Lizzie?

20:51.167 --> 20:52.877
Is something the matter?

20:52.877 --> 20:54.545
Father is dead.
Someone came in
and killed him.

20:58.300 --> 20:59.550
(SCREAMING)

21:05.723 --> 21:07.266
Help!

21:08.017 --> 21:09.519
Help!

21:10.269 --> 21:14.399
Dr. Bowen, help!

21:14.399 --> 21:17.319
Dr. Bowen, please!

21:17.319 --> 21:18.903
Dr. Bowen!

21:18.903 --> 21:20.405
(BANGING)

21:24.450 --> 21:26.911
Bridget. My goodness,
what is it?

21:26.911 --> 21:28.788
Mr. Borden.
He's been killed.

21:36.129 --> 21:37.339
(SNIFFLES)

21:43.761 --> 21:45.430
(ALL CLAMORING)

21:54.147 --> 21:55.399
Ladies.

21:56.733 --> 21:59.318
Officers.

21:59.318 --> 22:01.571
Would you like to
sit down, Miss Lizzie?

22:11.539 --> 22:14.250
Would you get him some water,
please, Bridget?

22:14.250 --> 22:15.793
Yes, ma'am.

22:26.053 --> 22:27.138
Lizzie, what happened?

22:28.306 --> 22:29.891
What's going on?

22:31.517 --> 22:33.478
My father is dead.

22:33.895 --> 22:35.229
What?

22:35.229 --> 22:36.773
Someone came in
and killed him.

22:38.525 --> 22:39.859
Your father?

22:39.859 --> 22:43.196
Oh, my God, Lizzie.
Oh, my God.

22:43.196 --> 22:44.697
Where is your mother?

22:45.407 --> 22:46.824
Who?

22:46.824 --> 22:48.535
Where is Mrs. Borden?

22:48.535 --> 22:49.869
Oh. Uh...

22:51.412 --> 22:54.582
She said she went out
to see a sick friend.

22:56.209 --> 22:57.627
I didn't see her go.

22:58.628 --> 23:01.047
Why don't you
check upstairs?

23:30.493 --> 23:31.619
(SCREAMING)

23:36.040 --> 23:37.124
The guest room.

23:49.595 --> 23:51.305
(BELL RINGING)

23:55.184 --> 23:56.520
(INDISTINCT TALKING)

24:03.276 --> 24:05.069
Do you need the room cleared?

24:05.069 --> 24:07.822
Gentlemen, we have to
take some pictures.
Stand back, please.

24:07.822 --> 24:09.658
Gentlemen, please.

24:10.992 --> 24:12.451
Doctor.

24:32.471 --> 24:33.598
(SIGHS)

24:35.850 --> 24:37.435
(BOTH SOBBING)

24:42.691 --> 24:47.612
I had no idea we could fit
so many people in this house.

24:47.612 --> 24:50.489
Miss Lizzie.

24:50.489 --> 24:54.452
I need to ask you
some questions,
if I could?

24:57.663 --> 25:00.875
I would like to know
what, if anything,

25:00.875 --> 25:03.294
you know about
what happened here today.

25:04.837 --> 25:06.464
I...

25:06.464 --> 25:10.509
I was in the barn,
so I don't really know
what happened.

25:12.011 --> 25:14.972
And what were you
doing in the barn?

25:14.972 --> 25:17.516
I was looking for
my fishing tackle.

25:18.726 --> 25:20.436
We are going fishing
next week.

25:23.565 --> 25:24.774
I ate a pear.

25:26.275 --> 25:27.736
I beg pardon?

25:27.736 --> 25:28.903
I ate a pear.

25:30.029 --> 25:32.782
I ate three pears,

25:32.782 --> 25:36.118
and then I came inside
and I saw my father.

25:38.955 --> 25:40.414
Perhaps we should
talk tomorrow

25:40.414 --> 25:41.624
when you're in
a clearer frame of mind.

25:42.375 --> 25:43.459
Yes?

25:44.586 --> 25:46.921
My mind is pretty clear
right now.

25:54.136 --> 25:56.347
If you could excuse me
for one minute.

26:07.191 --> 26:08.484
(DOOR OPENING)

26:12.989 --> 26:15.199
What are they going to do?

26:15.199 --> 26:18.536
That is the medical examiner.
They need to examine him now.

26:18.536 --> 26:19.829
In the dining room?

26:19.829 --> 26:21.455
Yes. Please.

26:23.582 --> 26:27.003
Miss Lizzie,
could you please
show me your hands?

26:29.171 --> 26:30.589
My apologies for this.

26:30.589 --> 26:32.759
It is just a procedure
for anybody who was
in the house.

26:33.342 --> 26:35.679
I understand.

26:35.679 --> 26:37.722
You're seeing if
there's blood on them.

26:40.099 --> 26:41.643
Over.

26:45.104 --> 26:46.689
Thank you.

26:59.160 --> 27:00.829
(CLEARING THROAT)

27:00.829 --> 27:03.039
Miss Lizzie,
what is this stain?

27:04.415 --> 27:06.083
Oh. (SNIFFLES)

27:06.083 --> 27:07.460
It's stew, I think.

27:07.752 --> 27:09.754
Stew?

27:09.754 --> 27:10.755
I see.

27:13.632 --> 27:15.176
Arms up, please.

27:31.442 --> 27:33.235
(ALL CLAMORING)

27:43.662 --> 27:45.331
District Attorney Knowlton.

27:45.331 --> 27:46.791
Marshall.

27:48.292 --> 27:49.753
Who are all these people?

27:49.753 --> 27:52.129
Neighbors.
Word travels fast.

27:54.507 --> 27:57.510
Has the Medical Examiner
determined a time
of death yet?

27:57.510 --> 28:00.221
He believes the lady
was taken at approximately
9:00 this morning,

28:00.221 --> 28:02.473
the old man
perhaps an hour after that.

28:03.516 --> 28:05.017
Was there a struggle?

28:05.017 --> 28:07.520
The setting seems
to be undisturbed.
Evidence of theft?

28:07.520 --> 28:09.897
Not at first glance, no.

28:09.897 --> 28:11.733
Marshall,
get this area secure.

28:11.733 --> 28:13.025
And get these people
out of here

28:13.025 --> 28:14.860
so we can conduct
a proper investigation.

28:16.737 --> 28:18.072
(SNIFFLES)

28:20.699 --> 28:22.868
You said she received
a note before she left?

28:23.619 --> 28:24.703
Yes.

28:25.412 --> 28:26.997
Do we have that note?

28:28.249 --> 28:29.291
Do you have the note?

28:30.251 --> 28:32.002
Why would I...

28:33.129 --> 28:36.257
No. Bridget, do you?

28:36.257 --> 28:37.716
No, ma'am.

28:38.885 --> 28:41.178
It must be with
Mrs. Borden.

28:41.178 --> 28:43.639
Mrs. Borden is
your stepmother, correct?

28:44.808 --> 28:46.725
Yes, she was.

28:46.725 --> 28:48.102
Miss Borden, did you
love your stepmother?

28:48.102 --> 28:49.562
How dare you
ask that question?

28:49.562 --> 28:50.855
Of course I did.

28:50.855 --> 28:52.523
Marshall, must we
endure this inquisition?

28:52.523 --> 28:54.316
Emma, it's okay.

28:57.736 --> 28:59.780
Mr. Knowlton, what else
would you like to know?

29:00.865 --> 29:01.782
Did you love your father?

29:01.782 --> 29:03.325
This...

29:05.035 --> 29:09.832
My father is
a complicated man,

29:09.832 --> 29:12.543
and he was known
to be difficult,

29:13.752 --> 29:15.754
but I loved him

29:15.754 --> 29:18.716
like any daughter
would love her father.

29:21.468 --> 29:22.971
(BOTH SOBBING)

29:34.148 --> 29:35.149
(DOOR CLOSES)

29:41.864 --> 29:44.325
Should we stay here tonight?

29:44.325 --> 29:46.118
I'll stay with you both,
if you wish.

29:46.994 --> 29:48.872
Thank you, Alice.

29:48.872 --> 29:50.581
Why don't I have some food
brought over from my house?

29:50.581 --> 29:52.666
We have some roast lamb.

29:52.666 --> 29:54.043
I am rather hungry.

29:54.043 --> 29:55.294
See you soon.

30:04.303 --> 30:08.015
I suppose we should move now.

30:08.015 --> 30:09.976
The Maplecroft house
is for sale.

30:09.976 --> 30:12.394
Why are you
talking about this now?

30:14.813 --> 30:16.983
You know, Lizzie,

30:16.983 --> 30:20.236
that I'm always here
for you, to protect you.

30:21.863 --> 30:25.783
Is there anything
you want to tell me?

30:25.783 --> 30:27.243
What would I want to
tell you, Emma?

30:29.245 --> 30:31.789
EMMA: Why didn't you run

30:31.789 --> 30:33.958
when you saw
someone had killed father?

30:33.958 --> 30:35.209
Why would I run?

30:35.209 --> 30:36.835
Did you know
the house was empty?

30:36.835 --> 30:39.047
The madman could've
still been in the house,

30:39.047 --> 30:40.924
he could have
killed you, Lizzie.

30:40.924 --> 30:43.634
It didn't feel to me
like anyone else
was in the house.

30:43.634 --> 30:45.761
But how could you
know that?

30:46.720 --> 30:48.097
I told you what happened.

30:49.306 --> 30:53.019
Do you think I'm hiding
something from you?

30:53.852 --> 30:55.729
No, of course not.

30:55.729 --> 30:56.897
Good.

30:58.066 --> 30:59.943
I'm so glad.

31:03.612 --> 31:05.656
You know why I didn't run?

31:06.907 --> 31:08.492
Why?

31:09.451 --> 31:11.704
Because I thought to myself,

31:11.704 --> 31:15.582
"That's what killers do.
They run."

31:16.875 --> 31:18.419
(SIGHS)

31:18.419 --> 31:19.962
I didn't want to
look like a killer.

31:28.178 --> 31:29.972
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

31:35.894 --> 31:40.024
♪ Cuba moon, pitch-black sky

31:40.024 --> 31:43.777
♪ Chasing smoke
on a thin white line

31:43.777 --> 31:46.030
♪ I've got a dangerous...

31:46.030 --> 31:49.908
One misused cleaver,
one broken ax handle,

31:49.908 --> 31:52.703
one ax head
without a handle, dusty.

31:52.703 --> 31:53.912
(INDISTINCT)

31:55.039 --> 31:58.042
Two larger axes,
both war axes.

31:58.042 --> 32:01.420
One ball-peen hammer,
one large pair of scissors.

32:03.005 --> 32:06.383
♪ Oh, I've got a dangerous

32:06.383 --> 32:10.971
♪ A dangerous,
dangerous mind ♪

32:13.515 --> 32:15.017
(DOOR OPENING)

32:15.017 --> 32:17.978
Good afternoon.
How may I help you?

32:17.978 --> 32:19.730
My name is Andrew Jennings.

32:19.730 --> 32:21.857
Mr. Jennings.

32:21.857 --> 32:25.028
I was a friend
and associate
of your father.

32:25.028 --> 32:26.945
I'm so sorry for your loss.

32:26.945 --> 32:28.530
We were having tea.

32:28.530 --> 32:30.657
Oh, I'm disturbing you.

32:30.657 --> 32:32.785
No, not at all. Join us.

32:39.958 --> 32:42.836
I'm surprised we haven't
met before, Mr. Jennings.

32:42.836 --> 32:44.088
The last I worked
for your father

32:44.088 --> 32:46.965
was on the Wilson Tanning
and Dye case.
Oh.

32:46.965 --> 32:49.052
Well, that's too bad.

32:49.052 --> 32:52.012
Those people said
the most terrible things
about our father.

32:52.012 --> 32:54.807
Yes, I remember now.
You were his lawyer,
weren't you?

32:54.807 --> 32:57.559
That's right.
In fact, I am counsel
for the family.

32:57.559 --> 33:02.065
I'm on retainer.
So technically,
I am your lawyer.

33:04.233 --> 33:06.860
But that was
a criminal proceeding.

33:06.860 --> 33:07.986
Are you a criminal lawyer?

33:07.986 --> 33:10.198
Criminal law
is my expertise, yes.

33:10.198 --> 33:12.074
Do I need a criminal lawyer?

33:12.074 --> 33:14.034
You were present
during a murder.

33:14.034 --> 33:16.829
I was not present.

33:16.829 --> 33:19.957
The police,
as you may imagine,
Miss Borden,

33:19.957 --> 33:21.959
are under a great deal
of pressure to apprehend

33:21.959 --> 33:25.504
the culprit
of this terrible act,
to find someone to blame.

33:25.504 --> 33:29.341
So tell me, Mr. Jennings,
who will they blame?

33:29.341 --> 33:32.053
MAYOR COUGHLIN:
So none of these
are the murder weapon?

33:32.053 --> 33:34.222
No, Mr. Mayor,
they do not appear
to have blood

33:34.222 --> 33:35.764
or any other matter on them.

33:35.764 --> 33:38.392
What about this day laborer,
Mr. Sousa?

33:38.392 --> 33:41.395
He's being questioned
right now
by the police in Tiverton.

33:41.395 --> 33:43.106
Hmm.

33:43.106 --> 33:44.523
What are
your thoughts, Hosea?

33:44.523 --> 33:46.942
We should look at
the children.

33:46.942 --> 33:50.904
(SCOFFS)
The two daughters?
Really?

33:50.904 --> 33:52.990
Yes. If you consider
the order of the murders,

33:52.990 --> 33:54.992
Mrs. Borden was killed
before Mr. Borden.

33:54.992 --> 33:56.160
Why is that so crucial?

33:56.160 --> 33:58.912
Because if Andrew
was to pass first,

33:58.912 --> 34:00.247
the entire inheritance

34:00.247 --> 34:02.583
would go to
Abby Borden's family,
not the daughters.

34:02.583 --> 34:04.334
MAYOR COUGHLIN:
But wasn't one of
the sisters out of town?

34:05.169 --> 34:06.253
Yes.

34:07.171 --> 34:10.299
But Lizzie was home,

34:12.134 --> 34:17.639
alone, in the house,
the entire time.

34:19.975 --> 34:22.936
Abby Borden was killed
at 9:00, Andrew at 11:00.

34:23.853 --> 34:25.898
A violent crime scene.

34:25.898 --> 34:28.984
Are we to believe
a stranger came into
that house, killed Abby,

34:28.984 --> 34:33.197
and hid for almost
two hours, unnoticed?

34:35.116 --> 34:36.241
It's inconceivable.

34:36.241 --> 34:39.036
Are you saying
that the girl did it?

34:39.036 --> 34:41.246
Yes.

34:41.246 --> 34:46.210
I think Lizzie Borden
killed both her parents
with an ax, in cold blood.

34:46.210 --> 34:47.835
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

35:00.140 --> 35:03.477
REVEREND BUCK:
We cannot bring these two
loving souls back to us,

35:03.477 --> 35:08.106
but we can celebrate them
by living our lives
the way they did,

35:08.106 --> 35:12.861
with honor and
dignity and piety.

35:12.861 --> 35:18.367
I also ask that we,
as a church,
as a community,

35:18.367 --> 35:21.328
offer love and support
to the poor, stricken girls

35:21.328 --> 35:22.621
left behind in this tragedy.

35:23.413 --> 35:26.209
May they both be comforted

35:26.209 --> 35:29.294
and may they both
realize how fully
God is their refuge.

35:30.837 --> 35:32.089
Amen.

35:32.089 --> 35:33.257
ALL: Amen.

35:33.257 --> 35:35.467
♪ All these troubles, Lord

35:37.386 --> 35:40.223
♪ All these troubles, Lord

35:42.350 --> 35:46.478
♪ All these troubles, Lord
They got me seeing blue...

35:46.478 --> 35:48.105
Hold it.

35:50.357 --> 35:54.362
♪ All these troubles, Lord

35:56.446 --> 35:58.574
I'll go determine
what this is about.

36:01.118 --> 36:03.246
Gentlemen.

36:03.246 --> 36:05.872
This is a private service.
What is the meaning of this?

36:05.872 --> 36:07.666
No disrespect, Reverend,

36:07.666 --> 36:10.002
but we've been instructed
to remove the bodies
of the deceased.

36:10.002 --> 36:11.254
REVEREND BUCK:
This is church property.

36:11.254 --> 36:14.382
Reverend,
we have documents
issued by the court

36:14.382 --> 36:17.175
instructing us to
exhume these remains.

36:17.175 --> 36:19.886
The bodies are to be
taken to Cambridge.

36:19.886 --> 36:25.392
♪ Lord, Lord, Lord ♪

36:25.392 --> 36:27.561
They're exhuming
the bodies.

36:29.354 --> 36:32.941
But how can this happen?
Are they not to be buried?

36:39.573 --> 36:42.117
All right, I'm done.

36:44.161 --> 36:47.456
Alice,
would you mind reading?
My eyes are too tired.

36:52.295 --> 36:56.257
"Reward offered.
$5,000 reward.

36:57.841 --> 36:59.926
"The above reward
will be paid to anyone

36:59.926 --> 37:02.305
"who may secure
the arrest and conviction

37:02.305 --> 37:04.348
"of the person or persons

37:04.348 --> 37:06.850
"who occasioned the death
of Andrew Borden
and his wife.

37:06.850 --> 37:09.227
"Signed Emma L. Borden
and Lizzie A. Borden."

37:10.271 --> 37:12.689
Mr. Mayor.

37:12.689 --> 37:14.524
Mayor.
Good day, Mr. Mayor.

37:20.155 --> 37:21.365
HILLIARD:
Good afternoon, ladies.

37:22.325 --> 37:24.117
This is Mayor Coughlin.

37:24.117 --> 37:27.245
Your Honor, this is
Lizzie and Emma Borden.

37:27.245 --> 37:29.498
It's a pleasure
to meet you both

37:29.498 --> 37:31.875
and please accept
my deepest condolences.

37:32.626 --> 37:34.378
Thank you.

37:34.378 --> 37:36.880
I'm here today
to inform you that
the county coroner

37:36.880 --> 37:38.423
has taken it under advisement

37:38.423 --> 37:40.343
to open and conduct
an official inquiry

37:40.343 --> 37:41.843
into the murder
of your parents.

37:43.429 --> 37:45.847
Your presence is requested
tomorrow morning at 9:00.

37:45.847 --> 37:48.392
An officer will be sent
to escort you
to the police station.

37:49.226 --> 37:51.186
Very well. 9:00.

37:51.186 --> 37:53.481
It's just a formality.
That's all.

37:53.481 --> 37:56.233
And what about lunch?

37:56.233 --> 37:57.859
We'll be done by lunch.
KNOWLTON: Well...

37:57.859 --> 38:01.738
And we'll get you home
right after.

38:01.738 --> 38:02.948
Thank you, Mayor.

38:02.948 --> 38:04.282
It was a pleasure
meeting you.

38:04.282 --> 38:05.325
Thank you.

38:10.747 --> 38:13.501
The Mayor in our house.

38:13.501 --> 38:14.376
What do you think of that?

38:14.376 --> 38:17.003
Lizzie, stop!

38:17.003 --> 38:19.465
Didn't you hear him?
We have to go to
the police station tomorrow!

38:19.465 --> 38:22.426
It's only a formality, Emma.

38:22.426 --> 38:24.094
It's interesting.
Interesting?

38:24.094 --> 38:26.138
Don't you think?
No, I do not!

38:26.847 --> 38:28.390
Our parents are dead!

38:50.537 --> 38:52.540
Good night, Emma.

38:52.540 --> 38:54.124
Good night.

39:34.122 --> 39:35.832
Look right.

39:35.832 --> 39:37.418
(REPORTERS CLAMORING)

39:42.672 --> 39:44.758
REPORTER:
Do you have anything
to say to the press?

39:44.758 --> 39:46.551
The   Herald  wants to know.

39:46.551 --> 39:47.803
(ALL CLAMORING)

40:06.655 --> 40:08.281
Give me your full name.

40:10.325 --> 40:13.078
Lizzie Andrew Borden.

40:13.078 --> 40:14.746
What is your
date of birth, please?

40:14.746 --> 40:17.791
July 19, 1860.

40:17.791 --> 40:18.834
Your mother
is not living?

40:19.918 --> 40:21.462
No, sir.
When did she die?

40:23.631 --> 40:26.509
She died when I was
two years old.

40:26.509 --> 40:28.718
You don't
remember her, then?

40:28.718 --> 40:30.136
No, sir.

40:34.642 --> 40:36.519
Have you any idea
how much your father
was worth?

40:37.686 --> 40:39.522
No, sir.

40:39.522 --> 40:40.730
Have you ever
formed an opinion?

40:44.527 --> 40:45.569
Never.

40:48.655 --> 40:52.951
You have been
on pleasant terms
with your stepmother?

40:52.951 --> 40:54.578
Yes, sir.

40:54.578 --> 40:55.954
Cordial?

40:57.498 --> 41:00.458
That depends upon
one's idea of cordiality.

41:10.760 --> 41:14.306
What dress did you wear
the day your parents
were killed?

41:14.306 --> 41:18.686
It was a blue
cotton dress with embroidery.

41:18.686 --> 41:21.479
Do you know
whether there was
any blood on that dress?

41:21.479 --> 41:23.899
The Marshall checked it
for blood, I believe.

41:23.899 --> 41:25.066
Marshall Hilliard?

41:25.066 --> 41:27.110
Yes.
When did he do this?

41:27.110 --> 41:28.612
When you were
all at the house.

41:28.612 --> 41:29.779
You mean the day
your parents were killed?

41:30.989 --> 41:32.908
That day, yes.

41:36.369 --> 41:39.582
Well, there was blood
found on that dress,
Miss Borden.

41:41.583 --> 41:44.545
It was not brought
to my attention.

41:44.545 --> 41:46.254
Where is that dress now?

41:46.254 --> 41:48.381
I have no idea.

41:48.381 --> 41:50.300
At home, I suppose.

41:52.636 --> 41:54.679
We'll need to see
that dress in evidence.

41:54.679 --> 41:55.805
What does that mean?

41:58.601 --> 42:00.894
We will send
a court officer around
to collect that dress

42:00.894 --> 42:02.228
and admit it into evidence.

42:12.739 --> 42:14.866
Lizzie?
What are you doing?

42:17.577 --> 42:18.620
What is that?

42:20.080 --> 42:22.750
It's that dress.

42:22.750 --> 42:24.501
Don't you need to bring that
to the police station?

42:25.502 --> 42:27.045
This doesn't
concern you, Emma.

42:27.045 --> 42:29.464
Lizzie,
you can't burn that dress
after they've asked for it!

42:29.464 --> 42:30.882
They'll think
you're hiding something!

42:30.882 --> 42:31.967
Just go back to bed!

42:31.967 --> 42:33.468
Do you want to go to jail?

42:33.468 --> 42:35.011
This will get you
in so much trouble!

42:35.011 --> 42:36.596
Just go back to bed, Emma!

43:00.578 --> 43:02.623
(INDISTINCT TALKING)

43:13.676 --> 43:16.386
Excuse me,
I'm here to speak with
the Staff Sergeant.

43:16.386 --> 43:17.679
Go right in, Miss.
Thank you.

43:20.598 --> 43:22.225
We attempted to
collect the item,

43:22.225 --> 43:24.519
but the officer was told
it no longer existed.

43:24.519 --> 43:26.438
No longer existed?

43:26.438 --> 43:28.940
What does that mean?
KNOWLTON: She burned it.
Your Honor,

43:28.940 --> 43:31.985
she knowingly
destroyed evidence in order
to conceal culpability.

43:31.985 --> 43:34.237
We asked for the dress,
she destroyed it.

43:34.237 --> 43:36.740
She didn't
just throw it away.

43:36.740 --> 43:38.783
She burned it.

43:38.783 --> 43:40.952
That is enough to
convince me of her guilt.

43:40.952 --> 43:44.289
Well, I'm just having
a difficult time believing
she could do this.

43:44.289 --> 43:45.832
Because she's a woman?

43:45.832 --> 43:49.461
Insane asylums are
full of insane women.
She's an insane woman.

43:51.629 --> 43:53.590
She killed her parents.

43:53.590 --> 43:55.258
JUDGE BLAISDELL: So do you
want to formally charge her?

43:55.258 --> 43:56.843
No, I want her to confess.

43:56.843 --> 43:59.763
Don't be
too ambitious here, Hosea.

43:59.763 --> 44:01.807
That woman
hacked her parents
to death with an ax.

44:01.807 --> 44:03.933
This is not about
my ambition.

44:06.102 --> 44:08.188
KNOWLTON:
You are in the barn,

44:08.188 --> 44:12.233
you are looking for
a tackle kit
for a fishing trip

44:12.233 --> 44:14.944
that is not going to happen
for another week.

44:14.944 --> 44:18.990
And yet there is
no fishing tackle
to be found

44:18.990 --> 44:20.617
and neither Bridget Sullivan
nor your own sister

44:20.617 --> 44:23.244
even know you own
a fishing tackle kit.

44:25.830 --> 44:27.874
And while you're in there,

44:28.708 --> 44:30.878
you stop to eat,

44:30.878 --> 44:34.255
not one, but three pears,
in a hot and dusty barn,

44:35.924 --> 44:37.258
next to a filthy
pigeon coop.

44:42.305 --> 44:43.973
Did you go into
the basement that morning?

44:43.973 --> 44:45.100
LIZZIE: No.

44:45.100 --> 44:46.976
Did you get an ax
from the basement?

44:47.644 --> 44:49.897
No, sir.

44:49.897 --> 44:52.900
Did you go upstairs
and have an argument
with Abby Borden?

44:54.275 --> 44:55.527
No.

44:55.527 --> 44:56.611
Did you conspire with others

44:56.611 --> 44:57.905
to do away with
your own parents

44:57.905 --> 44:59.781
in order to inherit
their estate?

44:59.781 --> 45:01.658
Absolutely not!

45:01.658 --> 45:04.452
Did you see
your father's face,
dead on that sofa?

45:04.452 --> 45:05.453
Did you see his face?

45:07.997 --> 45:10.792
Yes. Yes, I did.

45:10.792 --> 45:12.418
Did you feel
sorrow for the man?

45:12.418 --> 45:14.671
I... I was in
a state of shock.

45:15.755 --> 45:17.382
Remorse?

45:17.382 --> 45:19.050
Remorse?

45:19.050 --> 45:20.761
I don't understand.

45:20.761 --> 45:22.887
Remorse because of the fact
you slaughtered
the man with an ax.

45:22.887 --> 45:26.809
Stop it! Stop saying that!

45:26.809 --> 45:29.686
You are a murderer.
You lied to this assembly...

45:29.686 --> 45:31.729
These accusations
are slanderous
and unfounded.

45:31.729 --> 45:33.106
(SOBBING) Just please stop.

45:33.106 --> 45:34.691
You destroyed
evidence.
Just stop.

45:34.691 --> 45:35.775
And you killed
both your own parents

45:35.775 --> 45:37.026
in order to
garner their estate.

45:37.026 --> 45:38.403
Please stop. Just stop!

45:38.403 --> 45:39.737
Compel this man to stop!

45:41.907 --> 45:42.908
JUDGE BLAISDELL: Counsel.

46:02.385 --> 46:03.887
(SIGHS)

46:03.887 --> 46:06.431
Ma'am. You startled me.

46:06.431 --> 46:07.432
Sorry, Bridget.

46:09.267 --> 46:10.810
I understand
the police spoke to you

46:10.810 --> 46:12.604
for quite some time
after I left the station.

46:13.605 --> 46:15.398
They did, ma'am.

46:15.398 --> 46:18.902
They wanted to
know my whereabouts
at the time of the...

46:18.902 --> 46:20.403
On that day.

46:22.238 --> 46:24.657
What did you tell them?

46:24.657 --> 46:28.369
I told them I was
cleaning windows and such.

46:28.369 --> 46:31.539
Did they ask you
if you thought I did it?

46:31.539 --> 46:36.003
I told them there was no way
that you would
ever do such a thing.

46:38.838 --> 46:40.673
I appreciate that.

46:43.343 --> 46:47.180
Bridget, things are different
around the house now.

46:47.180 --> 46:49.766
With money being
what it is,

46:49.766 --> 46:53.020
Emma and I can't afford to
keep you on any longer.

46:56.105 --> 46:58.274
There are enough funds here.

46:59.234 --> 47:01.319
It's three months' wages.

47:02.445 --> 47:05.323
Are you letting me go,
Miss Lizzie?

47:05.323 --> 47:07.575
That is what I'm saying, yes.

47:14.249 --> 47:15.792
You must be quite exhausted.

47:15.792 --> 47:18.836
(SIGHS) It was
a very long session,
Dr. Bowen.

47:18.836 --> 47:21.256
From 9:00 till noon.
Mmm-hmm.

47:21.256 --> 47:24.676
Well, now you can
get some rest.

47:24.676 --> 47:26.511
What is that exactly?

47:26.511 --> 47:28.179
It's just morphine.

47:30.265 --> 47:33.059
I'd never been in
a police station before.

47:35.061 --> 47:37.855
These small doses
are for you.

47:37.855 --> 47:40.858
You use them
if the anxiety
is too great.

47:43.194 --> 47:45.822
No more than two a day.
Very good.

47:47.282 --> 47:48.866
Thank you,
Doctor.

47:50.326 --> 47:51.703
(SIGHS)

47:55.164 --> 47:56.332
Emma?

47:57.918 --> 48:01.046
Do you think
there really was
blood on my dress?

48:02.380 --> 48:04.132
I don't know, Lizzie.

48:05.049 --> 48:07.510
Here. Just try and rest.

48:15.435 --> 48:17.103
(ECHOING)
Just try and rest.

48:17.103 --> 48:18.855
(SIGHING HEAVILY)

48:23.067 --> 48:24.277
Hello?

49:24.420 --> 49:25.880
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

49:35.515 --> 49:39.727
♪ Oh, look up, look down

49:39.727 --> 49:43.398
♪ Look out, look all around

49:43.398 --> 49:48.194
♪ Shook up,
shot down, shook out

49:49.112 --> 49:51.697
♪ Shake it all around

49:56.244 --> 49:59.914
REPORTER:   The New York Times.
What can you tell us
about the case?

50:03.042 --> 50:05.087
♪ Yeah, mama,
shake it, baby, now

50:05.087 --> 50:06.963
♪ Yeah, mama,
shake it, baby, now

50:06.963 --> 50:08.631
♪ Yeah, mama,
shake it, baby, now... ♪

50:08.631 --> 50:10.174
KNOWLTON: (ECHOING)
Did you eat breakfast
that morning?

50:10.174 --> 50:13.594
Did you eat breakfast
that morning in the barn?

50:17.348 --> 50:19.934
You said you were eating
in the barn, correct?

50:21.936 --> 50:25.022
I was eating, so yes.
Yes, I was eating.

50:27.316 --> 50:29.111
(SCREAMING)
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

50:30.278 --> 50:31.571
KNOWLTON:
Then what did you do?

50:35.450 --> 50:39.662
I asked her to
draw the curtains
because the sun was so hot.

50:44.709 --> 50:45.751
Asked who?

50:48.171 --> 50:49.046
(SIGHS)

50:49.046 --> 50:52.175
It must have been
Mrs. Borden.

50:52.175 --> 50:54.760
Are you sure you
were in the kitchen
when your father returned?

50:57.054 --> 50:59.140
When he returned,
I was upstairs.

50:59.140 --> 51:01.726
Miss Borden, you have
told us several times

51:01.726 --> 51:04.270
that you were downstairs
when your father came home.

51:06.772 --> 51:09.108
I don't know what I've said.

51:09.108 --> 51:11.486
I have been asked
so many questions,

51:11.486 --> 51:14.447
and I'm so confused.

51:14.447 --> 51:16.240
So you were upstairs.
Were you with Mrs. Borden?

51:16.240 --> 51:17.867
I don't know
a thing anymore.

51:17.867 --> 51:20.161
Were you with Bridget?
No. No.
Bridget was outside.

51:20.161 --> 51:22.163
Did you see
your mother upstairs?
Your Honor, please.

51:22.163 --> 51:24.832
Did you see
your mother upstairs?

51:24.832 --> 51:26.292
Miss Borden,
did you love your mother?

51:26.292 --> 51:28.253
She's not my mother!

51:43.142 --> 51:46.854
EMMA: Lizzie.
Miss Lizzie,
Judge Blaisdell sent me.

51:50.900 --> 51:54.070
"Lizzie A. Borden,
the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts complains

51:54.070 --> 51:58.241
"that you did, feloniously
and with malice aforethought,

51:58.241 --> 52:00.368
"make assault with
a certain sharp instrument

52:00.368 --> 52:03.579
"in and upon the head
of Andrew J. Borden."

52:03.579 --> 52:06.290
Please, stop.
What exactly does this mean?

52:06.290 --> 52:07.875
We have to take you
into custody.

52:07.875 --> 52:10.586
Under whose authority?
I was sent by court decree.

52:10.586 --> 52:12.046
(SIGHS)

52:12.046 --> 52:13.422
You know what they think.

52:15.175 --> 52:17.677
Your attorney, Mr. Jennings,
is waiting for you.

52:17.677 --> 52:19.262
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

52:23.724 --> 52:27.562
♪ When the aim is low
When the shot is wide

52:27.562 --> 52:29.522
♪ You got to
set your shoulder

52:29.522 --> 52:31.190
♪ Keep 'em satisfied

52:31.190 --> 52:34.610
♪ And the honey flows
And the black is white

52:34.610 --> 52:36.571
♪ You got to lock and load

52:36.571 --> 52:38.948
♪ And leave
your soul behind ♪

52:47.957 --> 52:49.375
(DOOR OPENING)

52:52.253 --> 52:53.504
Why is this happening?

52:53.504 --> 52:56.258
Lizzie, you are under arrest.

52:56.258 --> 52:57.466
They're officially
filing charges.

52:57.466 --> 52:59.261
They believe
you killed your parents.

52:59.261 --> 53:00.678
How could they believe that?

53:00.678 --> 53:04.307
The prosecutor
is very determined.

53:04.307 --> 53:06.851
And why have I been brought
all the way out to this place?

53:06.851 --> 53:10.313
Because Fall River
has no facility for
housing female prisoners.

53:10.313 --> 53:12.232
You'll be taken care of here.

53:12.232 --> 53:14.483
We'll bring you
what you need,
meals, anything.

53:23.534 --> 53:25.412
And what will
happen to me now?

53:27.705 --> 53:29.249
(WOMAN 1 SOBBING)

53:31.293 --> 53:32.835
(WOMAN 2 MOANING)

53:42.637 --> 53:45.640
Are you telling me
I was arrested because
I burned an old dress?

53:45.640 --> 53:47.975
No. But they think
the act is enough

53:47.975 --> 53:49.727
to show intention
and motive.

53:51.520 --> 53:54.482
They looked at it once.
I was never told to keep it.

53:54.482 --> 53:57.234
Of course not.
It is not evidence,
not admissible.

53:57.234 --> 53:59.570
It provides no insight.
It proves nothing.

53:59.570 --> 54:04.033
It's that act of
burning the dress, Lizzie,
that created suspicion.

54:04.033 --> 54:06.035
Can they keep
lying about me?

54:06.035 --> 54:08.413
(SIGHS) Everything
they say is a lie.

54:08.413 --> 54:10.039
All they have are
the stories they create.

54:10.039 --> 54:13.626
Your statement at the inquest
is not admissible at trial.

54:13.626 --> 54:17.004
Everything I said?
Not admissible at trial.

54:17.004 --> 54:18.506
They didn't advise you
of your rights.

54:18.506 --> 54:20.257
They thought
you would confess.

54:20.257 --> 54:22.593
Why would I do that?
Exactly.

54:22.593 --> 54:27.139
We have the truth
on our side and we have
the law on our side.

54:27.139 --> 54:29.392
But you need to
think about this.

54:30.768 --> 54:33.479
Your case is now
headline news.

54:33.479 --> 54:35.357
Everything you say,
your every move,

54:35.357 --> 54:37.149
will be examined
and dissected,

54:37.149 --> 54:39.777
and you will be judged
by your actions.

54:42.697 --> 54:44.365
I hate this photograph of me.

54:44.365 --> 54:47.410
Do you understand
the gravity
of these charges?

54:47.410 --> 54:49.496
The penalty
for this crime is death.

54:50.162 --> 54:51.664
But I am innocent.

55:02.342 --> 55:03.676
I'm innocent!

55:23.154 --> 55:26.073
MAN 1: There she is!
MAN 2: Comment.

55:26.073 --> 55:28.242
MAN 3:   The Boston Globe
has a question for you.

55:28.242 --> 55:29.660
(ALL CLAMORING)

55:36.876 --> 55:38.294
(INDISTINCT)

55:46.010 --> 55:47.344
WOMAN: There she is!

55:48.387 --> 55:49.805
(ALL MURMURING)

55:56.604 --> 55:57.938
MAN: She couldn't
possibly have done it.

56:05.362 --> 56:06.406
She's pretty.

56:07.114 --> 56:09.200
She couldn't kill anybody.

56:09.200 --> 56:10.452
Are you well, Lizzie?
I'm fine.

56:12.995 --> 56:16.248
Upon the fourth day
of August,

56:16.248 --> 56:18.959
an old man and woman,
husband and wife,

56:18.959 --> 56:21.086
each without
a known enemy in the world

56:22.129 --> 56:25.049
and in their own home,

56:25.049 --> 56:31.013
upon a frequented street
in the most populous city
in this county,

56:31.013 --> 56:37.728
were first one,
then after an interval of
almost two hours, another,

56:37.728 --> 56:42.066
severally killed
by unlawful human agency.

56:42.942 --> 56:45.528
Fact

56:45.528 --> 56:50.366
and fiction have furnished
many astounding examples
of crime

56:50.366 --> 56:54.119
that have shocked
the senses and staggered
the reason of men.

56:55.538 --> 56:57.206
Yet, I think not one

56:58.499 --> 57:01.168
has ever surpassed
the mystery of this case.

57:02.086 --> 57:04.338
KNOWLTON: Today,

57:04.338 --> 57:10.595
this woman of
good social position
and unquestionable character,

57:10.595 --> 57:14.641
a member of
a Christian church,
active in its good works,

57:14.641 --> 57:17.017
the very own daughter
of one of the victims,

57:17.017 --> 57:19.103
sits before you
in this court,

57:20.104 --> 57:22.106
charged by the Grand Jury

57:23.525 --> 57:25.109
with these crimes.

57:26.068 --> 57:28.070
The brutal,

57:28.070 --> 57:33.576
indeed savage character
of the crime,
the audacity of its location,

57:33.576 --> 57:35.744
and the extraordinary
accusation

57:35.744 --> 57:38.873
that the youngest daughter
of one of the victims

57:38.873 --> 57:41.876
is the insane fiend
who carried out this act.

57:42.918 --> 57:45.337
KNOWLTON:
It was an incredible crime,

57:45.337 --> 57:48.507
a bloody
and unthinkable crime.

57:48.507 --> 57:52.094
Because the cold
merciful fact
that confronts us

57:52.094 --> 57:54.513
is that it was
committed by a woman.

57:54.513 --> 57:56.641
You might come to
believe that

57:56.641 --> 58:00.144
only a feral thing
could dispatch
their own forbearers

58:00.144 --> 58:03.022
with such malice
and impunity.

58:03.022 --> 58:09.571
You might wonder
what kind of dark heart
resides in that soul.

58:09.571 --> 58:15.702
But I am telling you,
that dark heart is in
this room right now.

58:15.702 --> 58:18.329
She did not strike
her father one time.

58:19.747 --> 58:21.081
Not once.

58:22.374 --> 58:23.542
Not twice.

58:24.793 --> 58:26.545
Not even three times.

58:28.464 --> 58:31.508
(CONTINUES STRIKING TABLE)

58:31.508 --> 58:35.721
But 11 times in the face,
with an ax.

58:43.938 --> 58:45.147
Harry?

58:45.856 --> 58:46.899
(SCREAMS)

59:16.553 --> 59:18.555
We're going to
take a short recess.

59:18.555 --> 59:21.558
I'll see counsel
in my chambers.

59:21.558 --> 59:24.395
JENNINGS: Your Honor,
look at the facts
of the murder.

59:24.395 --> 59:29.776
Female victim,
struck numerous times
with an ax, nothing taken.

59:29.776 --> 59:31.318
The killer hid inside
the house.

59:31.318 --> 59:34.113
Same time of day.
It's the same
modus operandi.

59:34.113 --> 59:36.407
And our suspect
was locked away in prison.

59:36.407 --> 59:38.867
We don't know all the facts.
We don't know if that was
a crime of passion.

59:38.867 --> 59:40.662
We don't know anything.

59:40.662 --> 59:42.622
The state has spent months
building a case
against this woman.

59:42.622 --> 59:43.998
We can't just
stop this trial
because of a similarity.

59:43.998 --> 59:46.500
And so the idea
being presented here

59:46.500 --> 59:49.796
is that there is
yet another ax murderer
loose in this very same city?

59:49.796 --> 59:51.338
JUDGE BLAISDELL:
I agree with Mr. Knowlton.

59:51.338 --> 59:55.092
The machinery
we have impelled
cannot be ground to a stop.

59:55.092 --> 59:56.803
The case will go on.

59:56.803 --> 01:00:00.597
And Miss Borden
will be tried in the matter
of which she was accused.

01:00:04.644 --> 01:00:06.478
The prosecution calls
Miss Bridget Sullivan.

01:00:07.312 --> 01:00:08.814
(ALL MURMURING)

01:00:23.162 --> 01:00:24.788
Do you swear to tell
the whole truth

01:00:24.788 --> 01:00:27.207
and nothing but the truth,
so help you God?

01:00:27.207 --> 01:00:28.459
I do.

01:00:35.758 --> 01:00:38.469
You mentioned something
when we had our interview

01:00:38.469 --> 01:00:40.012
that I thought
was interesting.

01:00:40.012 --> 01:00:42.181
You said, in all the years
you worked there,

01:00:42.181 --> 01:00:45.392
you never saw Lizzie
give her father a gift.

01:00:45.392 --> 01:00:47.144
Is that a true statement?

01:00:47.144 --> 01:00:50.064
No. She gave him a ring.

01:00:50.064 --> 01:00:52.691
A ring.
It was from her
high school, I believe.

01:00:53.860 --> 01:00:55.444
Other than this ring,

01:00:55.444 --> 01:01:00.157
did you ever see her
give her father anything
as far as you know?

01:01:00.157 --> 01:01:01.867
They weren't
that kind of family.

01:01:01.867 --> 01:01:03.202
What kind of family
were they?

01:01:03.202 --> 01:01:05.245
Your Honor,
is the witness expected

01:01:05.245 --> 01:01:08.165
to answer
such a broad question?

01:01:08.165 --> 01:01:09.833
JUDGE BLAISDELL: Counsel.

01:01:09.833 --> 01:01:13.670
You were present
on the morning
of the murders?

01:01:13.670 --> 01:01:15.005
I was there.

01:01:15.005 --> 01:01:17.382
We have established
that Mrs. Borden

01:01:17.382 --> 01:01:20.302
was killed around 9:30
that morning.

01:01:20.302 --> 01:01:22.638
Was Lizzie present
at that time?

01:01:22.638 --> 01:01:23.639
At 9:30?

01:01:24.431 --> 01:01:26.058
Around that time, yes.

01:01:26.058 --> 01:01:29.978
And then around 10:30,
when Mr. Borden came home,

01:01:29.978 --> 01:01:32.856
you saw Lizzie
at that time also, correct?

01:01:32.856 --> 01:01:33.941
BRIDGET: Yes.

01:01:33.941 --> 01:01:35.734
Was this when you
had the discussion

01:01:35.734 --> 01:01:37.361
about Mrs. Borden's
whereabouts?

01:01:38.362 --> 01:01:40.114
Yes.

01:01:40.114 --> 01:01:42.825
She simply said
that she had to visit
a friend who was sick

01:01:42.825 --> 01:01:45.244
and you were to
finish the windows.

01:01:45.244 --> 01:01:47.746
Summoned by a sick friend.

01:01:47.746 --> 01:01:50.874
Was the friend named?
No, sir.

01:01:50.874 --> 01:01:53.001
Did Lizzie
show you the note?

01:01:54.128 --> 01:01:55.880
No.

01:01:55.880 --> 01:01:58.423
KNOWLTON: Did Mrs. Borden
have a lot of friends?

01:01:58.423 --> 01:02:00.968
Not many.
Not many or not any?

01:02:00.968 --> 01:02:02.803
Maybe one.

01:02:02.803 --> 01:02:04.930
Has she been known
to help people in need?

01:02:05.889 --> 01:02:07.558
Not especially.

01:02:08.809 --> 01:02:10.561
So while you were
being told

01:02:10.561 --> 01:02:13.063
Mrs. Borden was out attending
to her sick friend,

01:02:13.063 --> 01:02:17.317
the reality was,
Mrs. Borden was laying dead
in that guest room upstairs.

01:02:17.317 --> 01:02:18.819
Is that correct?

01:02:19.361 --> 01:02:20.445
Yes.

01:02:22.990 --> 01:02:25.827
I was upstairs

01:02:25.827 --> 01:02:30.497
looking out their window
and saw her walk out back

01:02:30.497 --> 01:02:32.833
and place the dress
into a pot
they had in the yard.

01:02:35.586 --> 01:02:36.963
Did she burn the dress?

01:02:38.046 --> 01:02:39.799
Yes.

01:02:39.799 --> 01:02:41.216
Was there any reason given?

01:02:43.260 --> 01:02:44.303
No.

01:02:46.388 --> 01:02:50.475
Your report indicates
that you saw a small stain
on her dress.

01:02:51.560 --> 01:02:53.478
I did.

01:02:53.478 --> 01:02:56.231
But you determined
that it was not blood.

01:02:57.566 --> 01:02:59.861
I saw a small stain
that looked old

01:02:59.861 --> 01:03:02.029
and did not appear
to be blood.

01:03:02.029 --> 01:03:05.992
KNOWLTON: What did you do
when you observed the stain?

01:03:05.992 --> 01:03:07.492
I asked Miss Borden
about the stain

01:03:07.492 --> 01:03:10.037
and she told me
she thought it was
from a stew.

01:03:10.037 --> 01:03:12.456
And that was
all you needed to hear?

01:03:12.456 --> 01:03:15.125
Feet away
from two deceased souls,
both violently murdered,

01:03:15.125 --> 01:03:19.087
that this possible
blood stain was stew,
and you left it at that?

01:03:21.548 --> 01:03:24.092
Would you explain,
for the jury,

01:03:26.888 --> 01:03:28.639
the basic nature
of your duties

01:03:28.639 --> 01:03:31.642
when you arrive,
92 Second Street,
Mr. Hilliard?

01:03:31.642 --> 01:03:35.896
I secure the area
known as the crime scene,
in this case, the house,

01:03:35.896 --> 01:03:39.358
and I conduct
interviews with anybody
who might have been present,

01:03:39.358 --> 01:03:41.818
uh, what is known as
the eyewitness.

01:03:41.818 --> 01:03:44.112
Did you interview
Miss Borden?

01:03:45.280 --> 01:03:46.657
I did.

01:03:46.657 --> 01:03:49.451
What did she witness,
according to her statement?

01:03:49.451 --> 01:03:51.871
She discovered
the body of Andrew Borden.

01:03:51.871 --> 01:03:53.873
She found
her own father, dead.

01:04:00.754 --> 01:04:03.925
JENNINGS: Did you examine
Miss Borden on your arrival

01:04:03.925 --> 01:04:08.054
for any marks
or for any blood
on her person?

01:04:08.054 --> 01:04:11.014
Yes, I examined her
for blood or injury.

01:04:11.014 --> 01:04:14.768
Miss Lizzie,
could you please
show me your hands?

01:04:14.768 --> 01:04:16.436
JENNINGS:
And you found neither?

01:04:16.436 --> 01:04:17.854
I did not.

01:04:17.854 --> 01:04:22.234
The records do indicate
that you did find
a small stain.

01:04:22.234 --> 01:04:24.152
The nature
of the assault

01:04:24.152 --> 01:04:26.738
would have produced
much more blood
than a single stain.

01:04:26.738 --> 01:04:29.075
KNOWLTON: Unsolicited!

01:04:29.075 --> 01:04:33.495
Can the testimony adhere
to what is known
and not what is assumed?

01:04:33.495 --> 01:04:36.790
Is this your first visit
to a violent crime scene?

01:04:36.790 --> 01:04:38.000
It is not.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:40.877
And is it your opinion
that a bloody crime scene

01:04:40.877 --> 01:04:42.462
is likely to produce
a situation

01:04:42.462 --> 01:04:45.007
in which blood would be found
on the perpetrator?

01:04:45.007 --> 01:04:46.341
That is often the case, yes.

01:04:46.341 --> 01:04:48.468
Did you, on arrival
to 92 Second Street,

01:04:48.468 --> 01:04:51.763
find any evidence of blood
on anyone in the house?

01:04:51.763 --> 01:04:53.432
I did not.
Thank you.

01:04:54.976 --> 01:04:56.351
KNOWLTON: Did Lizzie Borden
visit your pharmacy

01:04:56.351 --> 01:04:58.437
in the days leading up
to her parents' deaths?

01:04:58.895 --> 01:05:01.107
She did.

01:05:01.107 --> 01:05:03.608
What did she
wish to procure?

01:05:03.608 --> 01:05:07.279
Potassium cyanide,
a very toxic poison.

01:05:07.279 --> 01:05:11.616
Excuse me, Mr. Bence.
Will this powder kill
the rats in my attic?

01:05:11.616 --> 01:05:15.620
She indicated
that it was for
a vermin problem.

01:05:15.620 --> 01:05:19.000
The Bordens
experienced extreme
gastrointestinal distress

01:05:19.000 --> 01:05:20.292
prior to their deaths.

01:05:20.292 --> 01:05:22.962
Could that be the result
of cyanide poisoning?

01:05:22.962 --> 01:05:25.422
It could, yes.

01:05:25.422 --> 01:05:29.926
Mr. Bence, did you sell
any potassium cyanide
to Miss Borden?

01:05:31.386 --> 01:05:33.055
No. I did not.

01:05:33.055 --> 01:05:34.431
(ALL MURMURING)

01:05:35.891 --> 01:05:37.851
Did either Abby
or Andrew Borden

01:05:37.851 --> 01:05:40.062
show any signs of
a defensive wound?

01:05:40.062 --> 01:05:41.229
Neither did.

01:05:41.229 --> 01:05:43.857
No marks or cuts
on their hands?

01:05:43.857 --> 01:05:45.150
No, none at all.

01:05:45.150 --> 01:05:48.278
Anything to show
that they fought
for their lives?

01:05:49.821 --> 01:05:51.531
No.

01:05:51.531 --> 01:05:53.450
Can it be ascertained
that the first blow
to Andrew Borden

01:05:53.450 --> 01:05:54.826
was enough to kill him?

01:05:55.660 --> 01:05:56.953
Yes.

01:05:56.953 --> 01:06:01.000
Evidence of incised
wound 4 inches long,

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:02.959
beginning at the cavity
of the left eye,

01:06:02.959 --> 01:06:05.046
reaching to lower
edge of lower jaw,

01:06:05.046 --> 01:06:09.424
cutting through nose,
upper lip, lower lip,
and slightly into bone.

01:06:09.424 --> 01:06:12.135
KNOWLTON:
So the first strike
was the fatal strike?

01:06:12.135 --> 01:06:13.512
In my opinion, yes.

01:06:13.512 --> 01:06:14.971
And how many times
was he struck?

01:06:15.847 --> 01:06:17.516
Eleven.

01:06:17.516 --> 01:06:23.522
So a single strike
with an ax killed him,
and then 10 more times.

01:06:25.440 --> 01:06:28.652
Your post mortem report
from the scene of the crime
indicates that

01:06:28.652 --> 01:06:32.280
you found that
Abby Borden died
around 9:30 in the morning

01:06:32.280 --> 01:06:35.117
and Andrew close to 11:00.

01:06:36.493 --> 01:06:38.453
How can you make
such a determination?

01:06:38.453 --> 01:06:40.580
Well, judging by
the state of rigor,

01:06:40.580 --> 01:06:42.582
the condition of the wounds,
and the texture of the blood,

01:06:42.582 --> 01:06:46.169
I would say
more than an hour
passed between each act.

01:06:46.169 --> 01:06:50.549
So the picture
that's starting to form
seems to emerge thusly.

01:06:50.549 --> 01:06:55.096
Someone killed Abby Borden
with incredible violence.

01:06:58.014 --> 01:06:59.516
Then paused,

01:07:00.350 --> 01:07:02.436
somehow, somewhere,

01:07:04.771 --> 01:07:06.065
for almost two hours.

01:07:07.649 --> 01:07:11.027
Then managed to
repeat the crime
on a second victim.

01:07:12.612 --> 01:07:15.198
All without being detected
by two women

01:07:15.198 --> 01:07:17.868
who were in
and around the house.

01:07:20.745 --> 01:07:24.208
Your Honor, as you know,
we've had the bodies exhumed

01:07:25.167 --> 01:07:28.170
and the certain parts
have been preserved

01:07:29.296 --> 01:07:30.297
to be brought here

01:07:32.216 --> 01:07:33.217
for your consideration.

01:07:33.675 --> 01:07:35.886
(ALL GASPING)

01:07:35.886 --> 01:07:37.596
JUDGE BLAISDELL: Order!
EMMA: Lizzie!

01:07:37.596 --> 01:07:39.014
JUDGE BLAISDELL: Order!
(GAVEL POUNDING)

01:07:39.014 --> 01:07:41.267
Order in the court. Order!

01:07:52.486 --> 01:07:55.947
KNOWLTON: There are
three exterior doors.

01:07:55.947 --> 01:07:59.285
The front door,
leading directly
from the sidewalk.

01:08:02.288 --> 01:08:03.455
MEDICAL EXAMINER: All right.

01:08:05.540 --> 01:08:12.005
At approximately 11:00 a.m.,
someone stepped up
to Andrew Borden

01:08:12.005 --> 01:08:17.219
and struck him 11 times
with a hatchet-like weapon.

01:08:17.219 --> 01:08:22.224
The blows left a 4-inch gash
through his temple

01:08:22.224 --> 01:08:26.394
and cut into the bone
of his upper and lower jaw.

01:08:27.395 --> 01:08:28.813
Thank you.

01:08:33.609 --> 01:08:35.779
I've sent Alice Russell
a note advising her

01:08:35.779 --> 01:08:37.822
she's no longer welcome
in our home.

01:08:42.702 --> 01:08:44.205
They're having me
testify today.

01:08:45.538 --> 01:08:50.042
Mr. Knowlton
will try to intimidate you.
Prepare yourself.

01:08:50.042 --> 01:08:54.089
I'm nervous. I don't...
I don't want to
say anything wrong.

01:08:54.089 --> 01:08:57.509
What could you possibly say?
That I'm capable of murder?

01:09:01.263 --> 01:09:04.432
No one in this town thinks
I'm capable of anything.
(CHUCKLES)

01:09:05.392 --> 01:09:07.394
Just tell them the truth.

01:09:13.524 --> 01:09:15.859
JENNINGS: Good morning, Emma.

01:09:15.859 --> 01:09:18.113
Would you,
for the members of the court,

01:09:18.113 --> 01:09:20.865
describe your relationship
to the defendant?

01:09:20.865 --> 01:09:23.493
She is my younger sister.

01:09:23.493 --> 01:09:27.455
Has Lizzie ever shown
violent tendencies

01:09:27.455 --> 01:09:30.625
or irrational tendencies
in her life?

01:09:30.625 --> 01:09:32.127
(GRUNTING)
(GLASS SHATTERING)

01:09:34.087 --> 01:09:35.546
Never.

01:09:35.546 --> 01:09:37.716
Well, then how would
you describe her?

01:09:39.175 --> 01:09:43.389
Kind, gentle, devoted.

01:09:43.389 --> 01:09:46.890
She is deeply involved
in the church and
in the volunteer service.

01:09:46.890 --> 01:09:51.270
And how would you describe
her relationship
with your parents?

01:09:51.270 --> 01:09:56.026
She was
a good daughter to them.
Obedient, respectful, loving.

01:09:57.360 --> 01:10:00.947
Is this the ring
your father wore
on his fourth finger?

01:10:01.406 --> 01:10:03.033
Yes, sir.

01:10:03.033 --> 01:10:04.242
Did Lizzie give it to him?
Yes.

01:10:05.369 --> 01:10:06.995
Did he wear it often?

01:10:06.995 --> 01:10:08.289
He never
took it off.

01:10:09.373 --> 01:10:10.540
Did your father love Lizzie?

01:10:11.958 --> 01:10:13.377
Very much.

01:10:14.169 --> 01:10:15.837
Did Lizzie love your father?

01:10:15.837 --> 01:10:17.256
EMMA: Of course.

01:10:20.216 --> 01:10:22.802
Do you believe
your sister murdered
your parents?

01:10:23.887 --> 01:10:24.929
No.

01:10:25.847 --> 01:10:27.182
I do not.

01:10:30.894 --> 01:10:31.895
Thank you.

01:10:35.106 --> 01:10:37.442
(CLEARS THROAT)

01:10:37.442 --> 01:10:40.904
You said, "Of course,"
your sister
loved your father,

01:10:40.904 --> 01:10:43.573
because one assumes
a man's child loves him.

01:10:43.573 --> 01:10:45.450
But Bridget Sullivan,
in the house for five years,

01:10:45.450 --> 01:10:48.370
testified that
Lizzie never bought him
anything, ever.

01:10:48.370 --> 01:10:51.581
Bridget Sullivan is not
the most reliable person
in the world.

01:10:51.581 --> 01:10:53.667
Did she lie
on the witness stand?

01:10:53.667 --> 01:10:56.127
She didn't see
everything that
happened with our family.

01:10:57.212 --> 01:10:58.588
I suppose not.

01:10:59.964 --> 01:11:01.591
I want to ask you

01:11:02.884 --> 01:11:04.302
about the night

01:11:05.261 --> 01:11:08.307
of September 15th,

01:11:08.307 --> 01:11:10.475
when your sister
burned a dress.

01:11:13.395 --> 01:11:15.438
Yes.

01:11:15.438 --> 01:11:17.607
You were with her
when she was
destroying the dress?

01:11:18.484 --> 01:11:19.818
I was.

01:11:19.818 --> 01:11:23.405
Did she tell you
why she was
destroying the dress?

01:11:23.405 --> 01:11:26.908
We both agreed
the dress needed
to be discarded.

01:11:26.908 --> 01:11:29.244
You both agreed?
Yes.

01:11:30.496 --> 01:11:33.457
It brought back
too many terrible memories.

01:11:33.457 --> 01:11:34.708
We hated having it
in the house.

01:11:34.708 --> 01:11:39.587
So I said to her,
"Let's get rid of the thing."

01:11:39.587 --> 01:11:42.383
Lizzie,
you can't burn that dress
after they've asked for it.

01:11:42.383 --> 01:11:44.676
They'll think
you're hiding something.

01:11:44.676 --> 01:11:47.929
Were you made aware
that the police inquest
wanted to see that dress?

01:11:47.929 --> 01:11:49.473
Not until the next day.

01:11:51.099 --> 01:11:52.308
Lizzie did not mention it?

01:11:52.308 --> 01:11:53.309
Just go back to bed.

01:11:55.395 --> 01:11:56.396
No.

01:11:58.606 --> 01:12:01.485
KNOWLTON: I gave her
those exact instructions

01:12:01.485 --> 01:12:04.571
on the day
the dress was destroyed.

01:12:04.571 --> 01:12:07.657
Did you
or did you not conspire

01:12:07.657 --> 01:12:10.201
to destroy that dress
because you knew
there was blood on it?

01:12:10.201 --> 01:12:11.495
No, I did not.

01:12:11.495 --> 01:12:13.329
Did you or did you not
burn that dress

01:12:13.329 --> 01:12:15.416
to destroy evidence of
your parents' murder?

01:12:15.416 --> 01:12:17.500
No, I did not.

01:12:17.500 --> 01:12:19.503
If Lizzie did
something that was wrong

01:12:19.503 --> 01:12:21.505
by burning that dress,
then it was my fault.

01:12:21.505 --> 01:12:22.422
I told her to do it.

01:12:22.422 --> 01:12:24.048
Why did you tell her
to do it?

01:12:24.048 --> 01:12:27.343
Because it was
old and terrible
and we wanted it gone.

01:12:30.388 --> 01:12:33.475
Because it was
old and terrible

01:12:35.519 --> 01:12:37.396
and you wanted it gone.

01:12:43.443 --> 01:12:45.320
(ALL CLAMORING)
REPORTER 1: Emma!

01:12:45.320 --> 01:12:46.863
REPORTER 2:
Tell us the truth,
Miss Borden.

01:12:46.863 --> 01:12:48.448
REPORTER 1:
What did you tell them?

01:12:48.448 --> 01:12:50.742
WOMAN 1: Emma!
What's happening?

01:12:50.742 --> 01:12:52.536
WOMAN 2: Is Lizzie guilty?

01:12:58.792 --> 01:13:00.502
(DISTANT GRUNTING)

01:13:12.598 --> 01:13:14.098
(INAUDIBLE)

01:13:24.108 --> 01:13:26.069
It was a terrible crime.

01:13:27.695 --> 01:13:28.780
An impossible crime.

01:13:30.490 --> 01:13:32.493
But it was committed.

01:13:33.619 --> 01:13:35.954
Mrs. Borden had been slain

01:13:37.539 --> 01:13:40.416
by some sharp
and terrible instrument,

01:13:40.416 --> 01:13:43.211
inflicting on her
defenseless head

01:13:43.211 --> 01:13:44.587
18 blows,

01:13:44.587 --> 01:13:47.173
13 crushing through
the skull.

01:13:48.509 --> 01:13:50.802
The prisoner
before you at the bar

01:13:51.970 --> 01:13:53.429
is a woman.

01:13:54.430 --> 01:13:57.559
It is hard to conceive

01:13:57.559 --> 01:14:01.896
that a woman could be guilty
of this crime.

01:14:01.896 --> 01:14:07.569
I need say nothing
with regard to the blood,
for there was no blood found.

01:14:07.569 --> 01:14:12.031
I need say nothing with regard
to the physical evidence,

01:14:12.031 --> 01:14:14.033
because there is
no physical evidence.

01:14:14.033 --> 01:14:17.328
There is not one particle
of direct evidence

01:14:17.328 --> 01:14:19.706
linking Lizzie Andrew Borden
to this crime.

01:14:21.625 --> 01:14:23.793
No thief did this.

01:14:25.169 --> 01:14:26.880
No random assailant.

01:14:29.716 --> 01:14:32.802
There was nothing
in these blows

01:14:32.802 --> 01:14:39.183
but hatred, hatred
and a desire to kill.

01:14:40.561 --> 01:14:42.729
We have heard testimony

01:14:42.729 --> 01:14:45.189
of a stranger
who was seen about
the household

01:14:45.189 --> 01:14:46.482
on the day of the murder.

01:14:47.693 --> 01:14:51.404
They have produced
no suspect.

01:14:51.404 --> 01:14:55.701
But the mere fact that
persons unknown had
access to the property

01:14:55.701 --> 01:14:59.579
is more than enough
to introduce
an element of doubt.

01:15:01.998 --> 01:15:03.958
If you can even conceive

01:15:05.126 --> 01:15:08.129
of any other hypothesis
in which it is possible

01:15:08.129 --> 01:15:10.965
that someone else
did this deed,

01:15:10.965 --> 01:15:12.258
then you

01:15:13.301 --> 01:15:16.638
have a reasonable
doubt in your mind.

01:15:17.805 --> 01:15:21.517
Lizzie Borden,
loving daughter,

01:15:24.730 --> 01:15:29.275
never went up those stairs,
never went up those stairs
that morning.

01:15:30.569 --> 01:15:34.656
Something else
went up those stairs.

01:15:34.656 --> 01:15:38.868
Something unholy
and devoid of feeling.

01:15:40.328 --> 01:15:44.040
Something we cannot fathom
with our own minds.

01:15:46.125 --> 01:15:50.714
That was the Lizzie Borden
who pursued that poor woman

01:15:50.714 --> 01:15:52.548
up the stairs to her death,

01:15:52.548 --> 01:15:56.010
and then waited,
weapon in hand,

01:15:56.010 --> 01:15:57.428
for the appropriate
moment

01:15:57.428 --> 01:15:59.806
and did the same
to her father.

01:16:00.724 --> 01:16:03.393
To find this defendant

01:16:04.728 --> 01:16:06.771
equal to that enormity,

01:16:08.523 --> 01:16:12.443
her heart so blackened
with depravity,

01:16:12.443 --> 01:16:16.739
her very existence
such a web
of violence and crime

01:16:16.739 --> 01:16:21.661
is to find this
tender young lass guilty.

01:16:23.789 --> 01:16:28.376
But to do that, you,
gentlemen of the jury,

01:16:29.752 --> 01:16:31.546
you must allow your minds

01:16:31.546 --> 01:16:34.382
to consider her
not just a brute,

01:16:34.382 --> 01:16:38.052
but a deeply, pathologically
depraved butcher.

01:16:41.764 --> 01:16:43.642
JUDGE BLAISDELL:
Miss Lizzie Andrew Borden,

01:16:43.642 --> 01:16:47.729
although you have now
been heard from fully
through your counsel,

01:16:47.729 --> 01:16:50.649
it is your privilege
to add any words

01:16:50.649 --> 01:16:52.859
you may desire to say
in person to the jury.

01:16:56.404 --> 01:16:57.572
(SIGHS)

01:17:01.451 --> 01:17:02.869
I'm innocent.

01:17:04.537 --> 01:17:07.290
I leave it to my counsel
to speak for me.

01:17:08.416 --> 01:17:10.209
JUDGE BLAISDELL: Very well.

01:17:10.209 --> 01:17:15.173
Now, gentlemen,
the case is committed
into your hands.

01:17:15.173 --> 01:17:18.176
This court now
stands adjourned
until verdict.

01:17:29.437 --> 01:17:30.772
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

01:17:32.774 --> 01:17:36.444
An hour and 10 minutes.
They must have known
all along.

01:17:37.236 --> 01:17:39.155
She will hang.

01:17:39.155 --> 01:17:40.198
BAILIFF:   All rise.

01:18:05.598 --> 01:18:07.892
Is it a bad sign that
they are back so soon?

01:18:07.892 --> 01:18:10.269
We must maintain
our composure.

01:18:12.021 --> 01:18:14.398
Lizzie Andrew Borden,
stand up.

01:18:20.613 --> 01:18:24.450
Gentlemen of the jury,
have you agreed
upon your verdict?

01:18:25.744 --> 01:18:26.786
We have.

01:18:26.786 --> 01:18:28.914
Please return
the paper to the court.

01:18:52.770 --> 01:18:56.232
Mr. Foreman,
look upon the prisoner.

01:18:56.232 --> 01:18:58.860
Prisoner,
look upon the foreman.

01:19:03.531 --> 01:19:07.828
What say you, Mr. Foreman,
of the charge against
Lizzie Andrew Borden?

01:19:10.914 --> 01:19:12.206
Not guilty.

01:19:12.206 --> 01:19:14.000
(ALL GASP)

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:15.543
(ALL CLAMORING)

01:19:19.172 --> 01:19:20.423
(GAVEL POUNDING)

01:19:21.967 --> 01:19:23.426
Order! Order, please!

01:19:23.426 --> 01:19:26.012
Business of this court
is concluded.

